Carson, thanks! Let me answer your questions and flag a timing issue.

**Timing: the team hasn't reached consensus on the task breakdown yet.** The team lead explicitly said "do NOT start any feature work until the task breakdown is agreed upon." So I'm not writing auth form CSS right now. But I can share my thinking so we're aligned when the time comes.

**File organization:** Everything stays in `main.css` within the components layer. For a project this size, splitting into multiple CSS files adds import management overhead with no real benefit. The cascade layers already provide logical separation. If the components layer grows past ~200 lines, we can revisit, but I doubt a todo app will get there.

**HTMX utility styles:** Agree, these are needed. I'd put them in the components layer as you showed. I planned to add them as part of the "base template + HTMX setup" task (which the team is discussing as a new task before registration). They're cross-cutting -- every feature uses them -- so they belong with the HTMX foundation, not with any specific feature.

**Auth form component:** Yes, an `.auth-form` component makes sense -- a centered card with proper spacing. I'll wait for Steve Schoger's visual direction on the specific layout, but the token system has everything we need: `--color-bg-raised` for the card background, `--shadow-md` for elevation, `--radius-md` for rounded corners, spacing tokens for padding/gaps.

**Form error styling with `:has()`:** Love this. Your pattern is exactly right:
```css
.form-group:has([aria-invalid="true"]) input {
    border-color: var(--color-danger);
}
```

I'd extend it slightly to also style the label and show the error message:
```css
.form-group:has([aria-invalid="true"]) {
    & label {
        color: var(--color-danger);
    }
    & input {
        border-color: var(--color-danger);
    }
    & .field-error {
        display: block;
    }
}
```

The server sets `aria-invalid="true"` on the input, includes the error text in a `.field-error` element with `aria-describedby`, and CSS handles all the visual treatment. No JS needed for error styling. The error message itself provides the non-color indicator (text describing the error), plus the border color change and label color change give visual association.

**One pattern note:** error messages should be hidden by default (`.field-error { display: none; }`) and revealed by the `:has()` selector. This means the server can always render the error container in the HTML -- when there's no `aria-invalid`, it's hidden. When the server adds the invalid state, CSS reveals it. Clean separation of concerns.

Ready to implement all of this as soon as the task breakdown is agreed and the base template task is assigned.

